<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06231153 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06231153 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Hurricane Bob, packing winds near 75 mph, threatened to strike the Outer Banksof North Carolina today, and some residents and vacationers, spurred bymemories of 1989's Hurricane Hugo and warnings from forecasters, scurried toleave the coast. The hurricane was expected to move north-northwest, take aturn to the north and skirt the North Carolina coast, and then continue north,said Bob Ebargh, a forecaster with the National Hurricane Center in CoralGables, Fla. Traffic was heavy late Saturday out of the Outer Banks, a seriesof narrow islands running along the northern half of North Carolina's coast.The area is a popular weekend spot for beachgoers and sport fishermen.;   State officials recommended that people cancel plans to visit the area today,and the National Park Service closed its campgrounds on the Outer Banks. &quot;Withthe unpredictable nature of this storm, it is better to be safe than sorry,&quot;said Joe Myers, state emergency management director.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CAROLINA VACATIONERS EVACUATE AS HURRICANEBOB THREATENS COAST  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910818  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  162  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday August 18, 199100231153,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>